Placemark.description:
County: Murray
Murray County, in northwest Georgia, is a dry county, although the city of Eton allows the sale of liquor at a local level.

County: Fannin
sale of beer in restaurants only

County: White
White County, in northeast Georgia, is a dry county except in the city limits of Helen, Georgia and beer and wine outside of the city limits of Cleveland, Georgia (effective January 1, 2009).

County: Dawson
was historically noted for being a heavy Moonshine county but was a dry county until recently with the first package store opening on July 27, 2007.

County: Franklin
Franklin County is a dry county, though several towns within the county are not.

County: Hart
Hart County in northeast Georgia is currently a dry county which prohibits the sale of liquor, yet a referendum was voted on in the general election on November 6, 2007 to allow the sale of liquor by the drink.

County: Butts
prohibits the sale of liquor. Sells only beer and wine.

County: Jones
Jones County in central Georgia is a partially dry county with no alcohol sales on Sundays, and prohibiting liquor sales except by the drink.

County: Effingham
near Savannah, Georgia, is a partially dry county. Sale of liquor is prohibited, but the sale of beer and wine is allowed.

County: Brooks
prohibits the sale of alcohol except beer and wine, with no sales on Sunday. The city of Quitman, within Brooks County, has allowed the sale of alcohol other than beer and wine in restaurants only since 2005. The new law was passed by Quitman voters despite fierce opposition from local religious and community leaders.
